 1201":"before 2 April 1201","1158":"1158","1202":"1202","1201":"1201","1145":"1145","1155":"1155","Beaudeset Castle, Warwickshire, England":"Castle Liberty, Warwickshire, England","Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Montfort","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and Breton: variant of   Monfort   1. This surname is most common in Brittany and Haute-Savoie. See also 2 below.","Altered form of Dutch <b>Montfoort</b>: habitational name from Montfoort in Utrecht. It is a cognate of 1 above (see   Monfort   1) and also its altered form (or perhaps vice versa).","English (of Norman origin): very rare variant of   Mountford  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Monfort","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French/Haitian Jacques, Marcel, Monique, Wilner.","French and Breton: habitational name from any of numerous places called Montfort, from Old French <i>mont</i> ‘hill’ (see   Mont   1) + <i>fort</i> ‘strong, impregnable’ (from Latin <i>fortis</i>). This surname is by far most common in Brittany. It is also found in Haiti. Compare   Montfort   1, see also 2 below.","Altered form of Dutch <b>Montfoort</b>, a variant of   Montfort   2 and also a cognate of the French name in 1 above and an altered form of its variant   Montfort   1 (or perhaps vice versa)."]},{"name":"Monforte","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Carmela, Carmine, Rocco, Rosaria, Sal.  Spanish Carlos, Francisco, Luis, Medardo.","Italian and Spanish: habitational name from any of numerous places called Monforte, from Latin <i>mons</i> ‘mountain’ (genitive <i>montis</i>) + <i>fortis</i> ‘strong’, probably a reference to the strategic position of these locations.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Montfort  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Juliana","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Julianus</i> (  see  Julian  ), which was revived in England in the 18th century and has been used occasionally ever since."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Juliana de Montfort was born in 1155, in Castle Liberty, Warwickshire, England as the daughter of Lord Thurston De Montfort and Lady Juliane Beaudesert De Murdac. She married Robert Daiville II before 1170. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in August 1202, in Egmanton, Nottinghamshire, England, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1155–August 1202":"1155–august 1202","1153–1183":"1153–1183","1155–1202":"1155–1202","1155–Male":"1155–Surnud","1158–Male":"1158–Surnud","1160–1197":"1160–1197","1162–Male":"1162–Surnud","1164–Male":"1164–Surnud","1150–1201":"1150–1201","1171–1242":"1171–1242","1175–Male":"1175–Surnud","1120–1190":"1120–1190","–Female":"Surnud","1190":"1190","bef 1170":"enne 1170","1242":"1242","1175":"1175","1120":"1120","1164":"1164","1197":"1197","1153":"1153","1162":"1162","August 1202":"august 1202","1150":"1150","1183":"1183","1171":"1171","1160":"1160","before 2 April 1201":"enne 2. aprilli 1201","1158":"1158","1202":"1202","1201":"1201","1145":"1145","1155":"1155","Beaudeset Castle, Warwickshire, Englan